This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the development of machine learning models for the identification and quantification of pathological features in OCT images. The use of CycleGAN, an unsupervised unpaired image transformation algorithm, also suggests a focus on image processing and computer vision. Additionally, the use of machine learning models for segmentation indicates a potential fit for the machine learning (cs.LG, cs.AI) sub-categories. The evaluation of the proposed approach on retinal fluid segmentation also suggests a potential fit for the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the use of OCT images and medical imaging techniques may also suggest a potential fit for the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
